{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508677"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.39,0.2,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41885"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3996"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26857"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1361"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42575"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41885"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two month history of increasing fatigue, generalised weakness, low mood, and a weight gain of 5 kg despite no change in diet. She works as a nurse on rotating day/night shifts and has uncharacteristically struggled to sleep between shifts. Her medical history includes recently diagnosed hypertension. Her medications list includes enalapril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she looks tired and has a full, plethoric face with central obesity. Her pulse is 92/min, blood pressure 150/94 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min and her BMI is 36\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ekg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Examination of her skin shows bruising on her arms and vivid pink striations on her lower abdomen. Baseline blood tests reveal a mild hypernatraemia and mild hypokalaemia. Suspecting the diagnosis, her doctor arranges a midnight salivary cortisol level, which comes back at \u0026gt;5 nmol/L [\u0026lt;5].\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urinary free cortisol","High-dose dexamethasone suppression test","Plasma ACTH level","CT adrenal glands","ACTH stimulation test"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms of generalised fatigue, weight gain and muscle weakness, in addition to insomnia and depressive symptoms are suggestive of Cushing syndrome, further supported by physical examination findings of high blood pressure, facial plethora, central obesity, easy bruising, and abdominal striae. Hypernatraemia and hypokalaemia are also commonly observed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiochemical diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s syndrome typically requires at least two cross-confirmatory results among three commonly-used tests: low-dose dexamethasone suppression test,\u003Cstrong\u003E 24-hour urinary free cortisol \u003C/strong\u003E(ideally 3 separate collections), and/or midnight salivary cortisol. Each of these tests has high acceptability in both inpatient and outpatient/community settings. (Midnight plasma cortisol may also be used in circumstances where midnight venepuncture is feasible, e.g. hospital inpatients.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, where the midnight salivary cortisol returns a result suggestive of abnormal hypercortisolism, a second test is required to confirm the diagnosis. Of the available options, \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary free cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is the only such test. In the GP setting, the patient is provided with a collection container and advised to collect their urine over a 24 hour period for testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce hypercortisolism has been demonstrated by at least two tests, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eplasma ACTH level\u003C/strong\u003E is the next step to determine ACTH dependence, which helps distinguish between pituitary / ectopic ACTH-secreting tissue versus adrenal pathologies underlying the Cushing syndrome.A \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-dose dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E helps localise ACTH-dependent disease to the pituitary gland. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E is performed to characterise ACTH-independent disease, which typically reflects either adrenal hyperplasia or a unilateral adrenal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EACTH stimulation test\u003C/strong\u003E is an investigation for cortisol \u003Cem\u003Edeficiency\u003C/em\u003E, as in Addison\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["At least two cross-confirmatory tests for hypercortisolism are required to diagnose Cushing\u0027s syndrome."],"references":[".Nieman LK. Diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s Syndrome in the Modern Era. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2018;47(2):259-273. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29754631/","Nieman LK. Cushing\u0027s syndrome: update on signs, symptoms and biochemical screening. Eur J Endocrinol. 2015;173(4):M33-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4553096/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26857"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26857"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-25T21:50:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T14:35:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3996"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41885"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78